16:50.343 --> 16:51.469
JOE: Mr. King,

16:52.970 --> 16:54.639
here come a bunch of cars,
it must be the governor.

16:54.722 --> 16:55.890
(SIRENS WAILING)

16:56.015 --> 16:59.352
Oh, no! He's early.

16:59.477 --> 17:00.728
Well, I got the gasoline.

17:00.812 --> 17:02.480
Never mind about the gas,

17:02.563 --> 17:04.272
let's get this place cleaned up.

17:04.357 --> 17:05.608
Just a moment.

17:08.027 --> 17:10.154
You must be insane.

17:10.404 --> 17:13.907
You said yourself, the public thoroughfare
is 50 feet from the center line.

17:14.032 --> 17:15.451
Well, the 50 feet ends right there.

17:15.535 --> 17:16.661
Teddy and Eddyjust measured it.

17:16.743 --> 17:18.246
- Right, boys?
- BOTH: Right!

17:19.247 --> 17:23.000
Back! Back! Back!

17:23.416 --> 17:25.044
What's it matter where it ends?

17:25.127 --> 17:27.380
This is State property, you idiot.

17:27.505 --> 17:29.048
This is private property.

17:33.052 --> 17:35.555
Oh, no. He's stopping.

17:42.395 --> 17:45.898
Mr. King,
what seems to be the trouble here?

17:46.107 --> 17:48.609
Governor, Your Excellency, I'm very sorry,

17:48.734 --> 17:51.195
but these people are obstructing
a public thoroughfare.

17:51.279 --> 17:53.573
We'll get rid of them right away,
Your Excellency.

17:53.698 --> 17:56.242
Trooper... Sergeant, arrest these people.

17:56.909 --> 17:58.494
- Good morning, Governor.
- Yes, sir.

17:58.578 --> 18:01.706
Morning, sir. Mr. Governor,
if you appointed this man

18:01.789 --> 18:05.126
I think it best you get out of the car
right now and put him straight.

18:05.251 --> 18:07.044
A man like you has got to know the law,

18:07.128 --> 18:09.046
and it's on the record now.

18:09.130 --> 18:12.091
You'll witness his violation
of a citizen's rights.

18:15.803 --> 18:17.972
Are you a student of the law, sir?

18:18.055 --> 18:19.807
A student? Why...

18:20.600 --> 18:23.102
Well, I know that the police
can't come on private property

18:23.227 --> 18:26.022
unless they's got a warrant
or is chasing people.

18:26.105 --> 18:28.024
Now, nobody can chase us.

18:28.107 --> 18:29.734
On account of we ain't running.

18:29.817 --> 18:33.196
So it's best they get off that
private property, right, Governor? Right?

18:33.279 --> 18:35.698
- Well...
- Sir, it's not private property,

18:35.781 --> 18:38.743
it's filled land.
Put there by the Highway Division.

18:38.826 --> 18:40.203
Well, you know what the law states

18:40.286 --> 18:41.913
about homesteading, don't you, Governor?

18:41.996 --> 18:44.707
Well, we're homesteading
from the end of the thoroughfare

18:44.790 --> 18:46.375
to the edge of the river.

18:46.459 --> 18:49.128
Oh, homesteaders, eh?

18:50.671 --> 18:52.506
Homesteaders!

18:53.966 --> 18:56.010
Any public land can be homesteaded,
can't it?

18:56.135 --> 18:59.805
Yes, sir. If they put up a roof and stay on it
for six months, they own it.

19:00.097 --> 19:02.808
The boy's right, Governor.
Well, there's the roof.

19:06.520 --> 19:08.940
They're on private property.
Would you get back a mite?

19:09.023 --> 19:11.234
- They're trespassing.
- All right, officers, get off.

19:11.317 --> 19:15.321
Respect private property at all times,
gentlemen, that's the law.

19:15.613 --> 19:18.366
Well, justice has been rendered.

19:18.658 --> 19:21.118
I'll see you later, Mr. King.

19:21.869 --> 19:23.621
Let's move along.

19:23.704 --> 19:26.332
- Take care of yourself, Governor.
- Thank you, sir.

19:29.335 --> 19:30.836
Nice parade.

19:31.837 --> 19:33.547
He's a nice fellow.

19:35.299 --> 19:38.761
Give three cheers for Pop.
Hurray! Hurray! Hurray!

19:38.844 --> 19:40.054
Stop that, you brats.

19:40.179 --> 19:42.098
- Brats.
- Who you calling brats?

19:42.181 --> 19:45.101
I'll take care of it.
Run along and play, kids.

19:45.184 --> 19:46.560
You gonna stand on our property

19:46.686 --> 19:48.938
and you're gonna give orders
like you're entitled to?

19:49.021 --> 19:52.942
That's a good idea.
Play it up while you've got the chance.

19:53.025 --> 19:54.860
Oh, yes, there's a homestead law,

19:54.944 --> 19:57.238
and you've taken good advantage of it.

19:57.363 --> 19:59.156
But there's other laws, Kwimper,

19:59.240 --> 20:02.201
laws that might cause you
a lot of unpleasantness.

20:02.326 --> 20:03.953
Such as? Go ahead, quote them.

20:04.036 --> 20:06.539
One, for instance, provides that none of you

20:06.664 --> 20:10.376
receive any more welfare benefits
from your home state.

20:10.710 --> 20:12.837
You're residents here now.

20:12.920 --> 20:15.131
I shall so notify the proper authorities.

20:15.214 --> 20:16.257
Pop.

20:16.340 --> 20:18.426
Pop, do you want me to throw this fellow
off our property?

20:18.551 --> 20:21.053
No, no, no, just leave him be.

20:21.137 --> 20:22.888
We'll listen and we'll learn.

20:23.097 --> 20:27.727
Learn this, too, then.
That well is probably unhygienic.

20:27.893 --> 20:32.023
That lean-to doesn't conform
to any zoning restriction I know of.

20:32.189 --> 20:34.108
Kwimper, I am proud of my job

20:34.191 --> 20:36.277
and of my responsibility to the people.

20:36.402 --> 20:40.114
I owe them my best efforts
to run your sort out of this area.

20:40.906 --> 20:44.410
You'll be hearing from me shortly.
Come along, Joe.

20:46.746 --> 20:48.331
Funny thing.

20:48.414 --> 20:51.625
I was just about to give him back his land
when he turned nasty.

20:51.917 --> 20:53.586
Now, I don't know what to do.

20:53.961 --> 20:57.840
Pop, didn't you mean what you said
about homesteading and all?

20:57.923 --> 20:59.800
But, damn it, I ought to stay here.

20:59.925 --> 21:03.596
But it's an awful lot of botherjust to take
that uppity hyena down a peg.

21:03.721 --> 21:05.723
- I gotta think it over, Tob.
- Well, Pop...

21:05.806 --> 21:07.600
I gotta think it over, Tob.

21:07.933 --> 21:10.811
Toby. Cross your fingers and pray.

21:12.813 --> 21:14.648
Pray for what, Holly?

21:15.107 --> 21:16.609
To homestead!

21:16.984 --> 21:19.779
To stay here.
To stay here for always.

21:20.321 --> 21:22.323
Why, that don't make a bit of sense to me.

21:22.406 --> 21:24.033
What's wrong with our own home?

21:24.116 --> 21:25.993
After Gertrude Patterson leaves, that is.

21:26.077 --> 21:28.621
Well, it's not our home, it's your home.

21:28.746 --> 21:31.957
But if we built a place here,

21:33.167 --> 21:34.710
it would really be part mine,

21:34.794 --> 21:37.797
and not just a place
I was allowed to move into.

21:38.756 --> 21:40.758
Be my first real home.

21:43.511 --> 21:46.764
I'm sorry, Toby,
if that sounds ungrateful.

21:47.306 --> 21:51.268
That's natural, honey,
I mean, women are just natural nesters,

21:51.352 --> 21:53.312
just like Pop said.

21:54.647 --> 21:57.316
Toby, a body would think a grown man

21:57.400 --> 21:59.443
could make up his own mind about things.

21:59.527 --> 22:01.195
Well, I agree with you there.

22:01.320 --> 22:03.197
I kind of like to make my own decisions, too,

22:03.322 --> 22:05.991
but I usually wind up doing
what Pop wants anyway.

22:07.660 --> 22:11.497
Don't you understand that I wanna stay?

22:12.331 --> 22:13.958
I wanna stay so much.

22:16.460 --> 22:19.130
I didn't realize it meant
that much to you, honey.

22:19.839 --> 22:22.508
Just don't get upset about it. I'll fix it.

22:22.633 --> 22:23.801
How?

22:24.677 --> 22:27.888
You mean, you haven't learnt how to handle
a contrary man like Pop yet?

22:28.013 --> 22:29.723
Watch this. Hey, Pop!

22:32.017 --> 22:33.310
Pop!

22:33.394 --> 22:34.979
Huh? Huh? Huh?

22:35.354 --> 22:37.231
We'd better get out of here.

22:37.314 --> 22:38.399
Who says?

22:38.482 --> 22:41.277
That King fellow is gonna make
an awful lot of trouble.

22:41.360 --> 22:43.904
<i>I'l</i> l break him off like a dry twig.

22:44.029 --> 22:46.031
Well, maybe so, maybe not.

22:46.115 --> 22:47.241
No maybe about it.

22:47.324 --> 22:49.118
Well, it's just that me and Holly here,

22:49.201 --> 22:50.578
we don't think you can handle a man

22:50.661 --> 22:53.205
as big and powerful
as a highway supervisor.

22:54.748 --> 22:58.127
Well, that settles it.
We're staying.

22:58.210 --> 23:01.088
We're homesteading.
We ain't leaving here until I say so.

23:01.213 --> 23:04.216
But, Pop, why,
how can we possibly manage?

23:04.341 --> 23:06.510
How will we manage?
That's my department.

23:06.594 --> 23:08.137
I'll take care of the brainwork.

23:08.220 --> 23:11.348
You young folks,
you take care of the work work.

23:13.559 --> 23:14.894
Toby...

23:16.061 --> 23:18.272
Toby, I could kiss you for that.

23:21.066 --> 23:24.570
One times one is one.
One times two is two...

23:29.450 --> 23:32.077
Wow! That's a monster.

23:34.038 --> 23:35.331
Is it good to eat?

23:35.414 --> 23:39.084
We ain't never gonna know.
He's too big to handle for this gear.

23:51.639 --> 23:52.890
What do you got there, a tarpon?

23:52.973 --> 23:55.351
I don't know,
but whatever it is, it's a whopper.

23:55.434 --> 23:57.436
He's too big to catch with a diaper pin.

23:57.520 --> 23:58.521
I'm trying to get rid of him

23:58.604 --> 24:00.231
just as much as he's trying to get rid of me.

24:00.314 --> 24:01.815
Trying to get rid of him?

24:01.941 --> 24:05.027
I've been paying $65 a day for charter boats
and never hooked one like that.

24:05.110 --> 24:07.112
I'd give $20 to play him.

24:07.905 --> 24:09.323
Well, you're mighty welcome, sir.

24:09.406 --> 24:10.699
Well, thank you.

24:10.783 --> 24:13.494
Just try not to lose the diaper pin
if you can help it.

24:13.786 --> 24:14.954
No.

24:16.080 --> 24:17.248
Whoa.

24:20.000 --> 24:21.794
(CAR HORN HONKING)

24:25.005 --> 24:26.674
Excuse me, sir.

24:26.966 --> 24:28.008
Hey, POP-

24:28.092 --> 24:29.093
Hi, son.

24:29.176 --> 24:31.178
- Get all the shopping done?
- I think so.

24:31.303 --> 24:32.972
Did you have enough money for everything?

24:33.097 --> 24:35.975
Yep, and a couple of luxury items, too.

24:36.141 --> 24:39.520
I went to a junkyard and I bought us a john.

24:41.272 --> 24:42.648
(EXCLAIMS)

24:43.440 --> 24:45.150
Ain't it a lover?

24:45.651 --> 24:47.319
It sure is, Pop.

24:48.946 --> 24:50.447
I bought some cheap lumber, too.

24:50.531 --> 24:53.200
I'm gonna build it its own little house.

24:53.450 --> 24:54.910
Is that a telegram, Pop?

24:54.994 --> 24:56.745
Yeah, from the government back home.

24:56.829 --> 24:59.540
That King fellow didn't waste no time
getting us cutoff.

24:59.665 --> 25:02.293
Well, don't you worry, Pop.
We'll manage.

25:03.002 --> 25:08.007
Ain't nobody can fret a family
got its own private john. Nobody.

25:12.845 --> 25:14.096
Need some help, sir?

25:14.179 --> 25:15.556
No, thanks.

25:15.723 --> 25:18.350
- He's putting up a pretty good fight.
-(LAUGHING) Yeah.

25:22.187 --> 25:23.522
(GRUNTS)

25:24.857 --> 25:25.941
Did you hurt yourself?

25:26.025 --> 25:27.192
Are you all right?

25:27.318 --> 25:28.694
(LAUGHING) I'm fine.

25:28.861 --> 25:31.113
I've never had so much fun in my life.

25:31.196 --> 25:33.198
I'm glad you didn't hurt yourself.

25:34.366 --> 25:36.535
Did you see the size of that one?

25:36.994 --> 25:38.662
The hook straightened out.

25:38.746 --> 25:40.497
It wasn't much of a hook though,

25:40.581 --> 25:42.416
it was just a diaper pin, that's all it was.

25:42.541 --> 25:45.419
A diaper pin, a pole, and a piece of string,

25:45.544 --> 25:48.464
and I had more action
than with $1,000 worth of equipment.

25:48.547 --> 25:52.551
Oh. Nope. Here's your $20.

25:53.052 --> 25:55.721
No, I couldn't take that.
All I done was lend you a fish

25:55.846 --> 25:57.139
and it was a public fish anyway.

25:57.222 --> 25:58.682
Thank you, sir.

25:58.766 --> 26:01.727
Oh, Holly, I can bend this back
into a hook again.

26:01.852 --> 26:04.146
I'm with you, sister.
Money's like a fish.

26:04.229 --> 26:06.440
Anytime you can hook it, you hook it.

26:07.066 --> 26:08.567
I'll be back.

26:10.069 --> 26:11.403
Thank you, sir.

26:15.783 --> 26:17.326
(CAR DOOR CLOSING)

26:17.409 --> 26:19.495
Oh, I know what you're thinking, Toby.

26:19.578 --> 26:22.206
It's a shame to take money
from a crazy man.

26:22.289 --> 26:26.460
We need this, and...
And the way he talked, he had plenty.

26:28.253 --> 26:30.422
Imagine paying money to fish.

26:34.426 --> 26:36.387
Here. It's yours.

26:36.470 --> 26:37.846
No, give it to Pop.

26:37.930 --> 26:39.139
(CAR HORN HONKING)

26:39.264 --> 26:40.849
ENDICOTT: So long.

26:40.933 --> 26:41.975
Bye.

26:43.143 --> 26:44.436
Holly.

26:45.145 --> 26:48.899
Did you hear what that fellow said
about paying $65 a dayjust to fish?

26:48.982 --> 26:50.275
Yeah.

26:50.901 --> 26:52.778
Kind of funny, ain't it?

26:52.861 --> 26:55.155
All the fish out here you want for free.

26:55.280 --> 26:58.117
The bait's free, hooks don't cost much.

27:00.661 --> 27:02.371
You've given me an idea.

27:02.454 --> 27:03.622
I have?

27:04.832 --> 27:07.418
Oh, such a wonderful idea.

27:07.501 --> 27:09.795
Oh, Toby, you're gonna be proud of me.

27:16.677 --> 27:18.595
Sure you don't need anything else?

27:18.679 --> 27:20.973
Nope, this is just fine.

27:21.807 --> 27:24.184
Now, really,
there are fish out there by the millions.

27:24.309 --> 27:26.687
Thanks for the information.
I'll pass it along.

27:26.812 --> 27:29.732
- You do that. Bye.
- Bye.

27:35.487 --> 27:37.030
MAN: Oh, it's a big one, ain't it?

27:37.114 --> 27:38.782
You've got a beauty there, miss.

27:38.866 --> 27:40.492
There's a beauty if I ever saw one.

27:40.576 --> 27:41.785
Wish you had caught that, huh?

27:41.869 --> 27:42.953
Anybody want any more coffee?

27:43.036 --> 27:44.955
Two cups, one with, one without.

27:45.038 --> 27:46.999
One with and one without.

27:47.124 --> 27:48.667
Throw in a couple of donuts, please.

27:48.751 --> 27:50.669
Couple of donuts.

28:01.013 --> 28:02.139
More wood, Teddy.

28:02.222 --> 28:03.474
Yeah, Pop.

28:10.981 --> 28:13.400
TOBY: $89, $90,

28:14.693 --> 28:15.903
$91.

28:17.029 --> 28:18.572
$91.50.

28:18.655 --> 28:19.907
- Is she asleep?
- Mmm-hmm.

28:19.990 --> 28:21.950
$92, Pop.

28:22.034 --> 28:23.452
$92.

28:23.535 --> 28:25.496
Well, that's fine for one day, son.

28:25.579 --> 28:27.623
That's what comes
of sticking up for your rights.

28:27.706 --> 28:30.042
Not running like a scalded dog,
the way you wanted me to.

28:30.167 --> 28:32.795
Oh, you was right, Pop.
I was wrong.

28:32.878 --> 28:35.422
You know, we'd better start a bank account.

28:35.547 --> 28:38.050
I've had nothing to do with no banks,
I ain't gonna start now.

28:38.175 --> 28:42.513
Now, Pop, banks pay interest
and you double your money before you...

28:42.888 --> 28:44.515
But I hate them.
Don't you, Toby?

28:44.598 --> 28:46.600
I never even seen the inside of a bank.

28:46.725 --> 28:48.352
I don't aim to.

28:49.770 --> 28:54.066
I mean, I'm gonna make
a few improvements.

28:55.442 --> 28:57.027
Lots, Pop.

28:57.110 --> 28:59.905
What we first need
is a line of pilings offshore.

29:00.030 --> 29:01.323
We do?

29:01.406 --> 29:02.699
So we can build a dock.

29:02.783 --> 29:04.076
A dock?

29:04.201 --> 29:07.120
Let me handle this, Pop,
I understand her a little better than you do.

29:07.246 --> 29:09.081
Now, what do we need a dock for, honey?

29:09.206 --> 29:11.667
Silly, so we can tie up our rowboats.

29:11.750 --> 29:13.210
Oh, rowboats.

29:13.585 --> 29:16.755
We need a rowboat
so we can row out to our yacht, Pop.

29:17.422 --> 29:20.092
Else how can we get out to that island
where our hotel is?

29:20.217 --> 29:22.678
Now, will you two stop that?
I mean this.

29:22.761 --> 29:26.223
We need rowboats so we can
rent them out to our fishing parties.

29:26.306 --> 29:28.767
Right now,
our customers are fishing off of that bridge

29:28.892 --> 29:31.144
and it belongs to the state highway.

29:31.395 --> 29:35.107
Now how long is it before that Mr. King
is gonna put a stop to it?

29:35.315 --> 29:37.526
- Be damned, but she's right.
- She is?

29:37.609 --> 29:39.319
Well, of course I am.

29:39.444 --> 29:40.946
So I talked to some folks,

29:41.071 --> 29:43.699
and it figures out
we can get some used rowboats,

29:43.782 --> 29:48.161
build a dock, and have
a real fishing place for about $2,000.

29:48.287 --> 29:49.705
POP: $2,000?

29:49.788 --> 29:51.331
TOBY: You done busted a bubble, honey.

29:51.456 --> 29:53.625
No, I've been asking around.

29:53.750 --> 29:57.170
There's a very good chance
we can borrow the money from the bank.

29:57.296 --> 29:59.882
Well, that would sure change
my opinion about banks.

29:59.965 --> 30:02.551
You mean they'll lend you
the moneyjust for the asking of it?

30:02.634 --> 30:04.011
And the interest.

30:04.094 --> 30:06.972
You gotta pay them back a little more
than they pay out.

30:07.097 --> 30:08.140
Oh!

30:08.599 --> 30:10.475
That's how they do it.

30:11.101 --> 30:12.436
Yeah, Pop.

30:12.936 --> 30:16.857
Well, will you go?
Will you go to the bank and borrow $2,000?

30:16.982 --> 30:18.567
Well, if it's that easy, let Toby do it.

30:18.650 --> 30:19.693
You mean me?

30:19.776 --> 30:21.695
Holy Ike, here I am dealing with banks,

30:21.820 --> 30:23.947
got my own fleet of rowboats,
my own docks,

30:24.031 --> 30:25.365
all because I wouldn't
let some government man

30:25.449 --> 30:27.826
tell me where I could stand
and where I couldn't.

30:27.910 --> 30:30.412
It seems there's a lot of money
in not doing what you're told, Pop.

30:30.495 --> 30:32.623
Yes, sir. Teddy, Eddy,
let that learn you.

30:32.706 --> 30:35.375
If you want to get along in life,
never do what you're told.

30:35.500 --> 30:37.753
Oh, for heaven's sakes,
don't tell them a thing like that.

30:37.836 --> 30:40.756
It ain't no wronger than telling them
they always gotta take orders.

30:40.839 --> 30:42.299
(WHISTLING)

30:46.303 --> 30:49.973
<i>Some folks tell you what to do</i>

30:52.059 --> 30:55.687
<i>They think they know more than you</i>

30:57.856 --> 31:02.736
<i>They insist that they're giving sound advice</i>

31:03.528 --> 31:08.825
<i>But as sure as you're living
It ain't sound, it ain't nice</i>

31:09.368 --> 31:13.747
<i>It just doesn't sound like sound advice</i>

31:15.207 --> 31:18.835
<i>Some folks like to be the boss</i>

31:21.046 --> 31:24.716
<i>They get up on their high horse</i>

31:26.593 --> 31:31.348
<i>Oh, they say that
you're getting sound advice</i>

31:32.057 --> 31:34.726
<i>There's one thing I'm betting</i>

31:34.851 --> 31:37.604
<i>it ain't wise, it ain't nice</i>

31:37.729 --> 31:42.067
<i>You won't like the sound of their advice</i>

31:43.735 --> 31:48.865
<i>Sound advice we're given, sound advice</i>

31:49.241 --> 31:51.868
<i>Just as sure as you're living</i>

31:51.952 --> 31:54.579
<i>If you're smart, you'll think twice</i>

31:54.955 --> 31:59.209
<i>When they start to sound off with advice</i>

32:00.919 --> 32:04.631
<i>Don't listen to their sound advice</i>

32:05.257 --> 32:06.758
(ALL CHEERING)

32:21.440 --> 32:23.400
Toby, 15 minutes left.

32:49.509 --> 32:51.553
Kind of like a church, ain't it?

32:51.636 --> 32:52.721
Yeah.

32:53.805 --> 32:56.516
What they got them poor fellows
locked up for?

32:56.641 --> 32:57.768
(CHUCKUNG)No

32:57.851 --> 32:59.436
They're tellers.
They cash checks,

32:59.519 --> 33:01.855
and make change and things like that.

33:01.980 --> 33:04.775
Oh, do they do the lending, too?

33:04.858 --> 33:06.485
Well, I suppose so.

33:06.693 --> 33:09.446
No, no, there.
Through the glass door.

33:09.529 --> 33:12.449
Now, Toby, you make sure
and don't forget to tell them

33:12.532 --> 33:15.077
that we grossed $92 on Sunday.

33:15.160 --> 33:16.286
And that you were in the Army.

33:16.369 --> 33:19.081
That's for character reference.
Okay? Now, go on.

33:19.164 --> 33:20.624
Hey, ain't you coming with me?

33:20.707 --> 33:22.751
No, I can't go in. I'm not dressed.

33:22.834 --> 33:24.503
You don't look no crummier than I do.

33:25.003 --> 33:26.296
Well, now it's different for a man.

33:26.379 --> 33:29.966
Now, you go on, Toby.
I'll be standing here, praying.

33:31.343 --> 33:32.677
(SIGHING)

33:45.649 --> 33:47.400
Anything I can do for you?

33:47.526 --> 33:50.862
No, I don't believe I have any use
for a policeman right now, thank you.

33:50.987 --> 33:52.072
All right.

33:58.995 --> 34:00.705
(BUZZER SOUNDING)

34:07.712 --> 34:10.047
- Oh. Pardon me, please.
- Oh, yes, sir.

34:11.049 --> 34:12.092
(BUZZER SOUNDING)

34:12.217 --> 34:13.760
Thank you, sir.

34:22.393 --> 34:23.937
What do you want?

34:24.020 --> 34:25.230
Money.

34:27.858 --> 34:28.942
(SHUDDERING) Money?

34:29.067 --> 34:30.318
There's nothing to be afraid of,

34:30.402 --> 34:33.029
in fact, I'm just as scared as you are.

34:33.112 --> 34:34.947
What's that you're saying?

34:35.072 --> 34:36.449
(MUMBLING)

34:37.909 --> 34:40.078
- You're feeling sick, huh?
- Yeah.

34:40.203 --> 34:42.289
Help, help.

34:42.581 --> 34:44.416
You look like you need help.

34:47.085 --> 34:49.129
Help! Help!

34:49.254 --> 34:51.130
Help! Help!

34:51.255 --> 34:52.882
(ALARM SOUNDING)

34:52.966 --> 34:54.759
(PEOPLE SCREAMING)

35:11.276 --> 35:12.819
- Get your hands up.
- Who, me?

35:12.944 --> 35:13.945
Come on, get them up!

35:14.029 --> 35:15.322
And drop this fellow on the floor?

35:15.447 --> 35:16.698
He's got a hostage.

35:16.781 --> 35:18.533
Open that dang door, will you?

35:18.617 --> 35:19.951
He says open this door.

35:20.076 --> 35:21.536
Get him before he can go for his gun!

35:21.620 --> 35:23.371
Watch out we don't hit Mr. Binkley.

35:23.455 --> 35:25.832
This man's in bad shape,
and he ain't gonna get no better

35:25.957 --> 35:27.584
if you fellows don't do what I say.

35:27.667 --> 35:29.169
One of you better call him an ambulance.

35:29.252 --> 35:31.546
Hold it right there or <i>I'l</i> l blow your head off.

35:31.630 --> 35:36.051
Well, the way you're waving that thing
around, you're likely to hit most anybody.

35:36.134 --> 35:40.931
And you better put yours down, too.
Thank you.

35:41.765 --> 35:43.141
(GROANING)

35:54.152 --> 35:56.321
Well, why don't somebody
get him a doctor?

35:57.864 --> 36:00.659
GUARD: Watch out, Mr. Endicott,
he's got a gun.

36:03.370 --> 36:06.873
Hello, Toby.
Are you holding up this bank?

36:07.624 --> 36:10.043
No, sir. ls somebody holding it up?

36:10.418 --> 36:12.212
Where did you get that gun?

36:12.295 --> 36:13.880
I took it away from him.

36:14.005 --> 36:17.592
He was over there waving it around,
he might shoot somebody.

36:17.676 --> 36:19.177
Bet it's even loaded.

36:19.261 --> 36:20.887
Let me have it, please.

36:20.971 --> 36:22.847
- Yes, sir.
- Thank you.

36:23.556 --> 36:25.517
Now, what have you done to George?

36:25.809 --> 36:29.020
Nothing. I just picked him up. He fainted.

36:29.521 --> 36:31.523
Are you all right, sir?

36:32.023 --> 36:34.943
I don't know, I...
Who are you?

36:35.235 --> 36:36.444
A friend of mine.

36:36.528 --> 36:38.989
He runs that fishing place
out on the new highway.

36:39.072 --> 36:41.700
Oh, well, I'm sorry.
lthoughtyouu.

36:41.825 --> 36:43.910
All right, guard,
open up the doors, please.

36:43.994 --> 36:45.120
It's all right, folks.

36:45.203 --> 36:46.538
Nothing to be frightened about.

36:46.663 --> 36:49.040
Just a mistake, everything will be all right.

36:49.165 --> 36:50.458
Toby, are you all right?

36:50.542 --> 36:52.210
Yeah, I'm all right, Holly.
I'm all right.

36:52.294 --> 36:53.378
Hello, Mr. Endicott.

36:53.461 --> 36:54.504
Hello, dear.

36:54.587 --> 36:56.798
Well, maybe you can
tell me what this is all about?

36:56.881 --> 36:58.967
I don't know.
ltjust seemed to happen all at once.

36:59.050 --> 37:00.719
Well, Mr. Binkley yelled for help and...

37:00.802 --> 37:01.970
No, I didn't.

37:02.053 --> 37:03.972
George, remember you're a vice president.

37:04.055 --> 37:05.932
Please get off the depositors' table.

37:06.057 --> 37:08.018
Well, I didn't yell for help.

37:08.101 --> 37:09.185
Toby did.

37:09.269 --> 37:10.520
Well, I thought he was sick.

37:10.603 --> 37:12.564
This man broke into the bank vault...

37:12.689 --> 37:14.816
I understand, guard.
Here's your gun.

37:14.899 --> 37:16.318
Just go about your business.

37:16.401 --> 37:17.694
Yes, sir.

37:18.236 --> 37:20.905
Well, let's get down to fundamentals.

37:21.239 --> 37:25.076
Now, young lady, what are you
and this gentleman doing in our little bank?

37:25.201 --> 37:27.245
We want to borrow $2,000.

37:28.079 --> 37:29.247
Please.

37:30.582 --> 37:32.459
Well, you went to the right person.

37:32.542 --> 37:34.878
George here is our loan officer.

37:35.253 --> 37:37.088
Could we have the money right now, sir?

37:37.213 --> 37:39.591
You see, the parking meter
is running outside...

37:39.716 --> 37:43.219
Well, Toby,
we don't do things quite that fast here.

37:43.303 --> 37:45.972
Why don't we come to my office?

37:46.097 --> 37:48.516
I think George needs to sit down.

37:48.600 --> 37:50.602
Well, come along.
Come along, George.

37:53.938 --> 37:57.859
So if we can get the dock
and the boats and the outboard motors,

37:57.942 --> 38:01.738
we could rent them,
make a lot of money, and build a house.

38:01.821 --> 38:04.616
Well, George here is the man
you're gonna have to convince.

38:04.741 --> 38:06.201
You frightened him to death,

38:06.284 --> 38:08.286
now it's his turn to frighten you.

38:09.788 --> 38:12.791
Mr. Kwimper, the bank must have security,

38:12.916 --> 38:16.669
well, that is to say that we have to be sure
that we'll get our money back.

38:16.795 --> 38:18.129
Now, this is Mrs. Kwimper?

38:18.671 --> 38:20.465
Oh, no, sir. She just lives with me.

38:21.841 --> 38:22.926
Oh.

38:23.009 --> 38:25.345
Well, I didn't mean to pry.

38:25.470 --> 38:28.640
I think you're getting
the wrong impression, George.

38:28.807 --> 38:31.267
How long have you lived
with the Kwimpers?

38:31.351 --> 38:35.063
Since I've been about 13.
Toby's Pop took me in

38:35.146 --> 38:38.149
for the same reason he took in
Ariadne and the twins.

38:38.233 --> 38:39.526
We had no place to go.

38:40.985 --> 38:42.737
Get the picture, George?

38:42.821 --> 38:44.114
Oh, thank you.

38:44.197 --> 38:47.909
Yes. Yes, sir.
Now, this land that you're living on,

38:47.992 --> 38:50.036
well, is it mortgaged?

38:50.453 --> 38:52.247
I don't know, sir.
We don't own it.

38:52.330 --> 38:54.165
We're homesteading.

38:54.290 --> 38:56.459
Well, we can't very well lend you money

38:56.543 --> 38:58.711
on property you don't own yet.

38:59.003 --> 39:00.463
Well, we own ourjohn.

39:02.006 --> 39:03.883
I didn't quite catch that.

39:04.342 --> 39:08.513
Ourjohn, and I guess we own the house
that we built for it, too.

39:09.722 --> 39:13.768
Yes. Well, let's move on here, shall we?

39:13.852 --> 39:16.062
Now, how about your car?

39:16.563 --> 39:20.525
Well, that car means an awful lot to Pop
even though it only cost $50.

39:21.151 --> 39:22.986
Besides, it's got fried hubcaps.

39:25.071 --> 39:26.281
Of course.

39:26.364 --> 39:29.242
Well, George, you've got to admit
he's been giving you honest answers,

39:29.367 --> 39:31.202
not cagey ones, but honest.

39:31.327 --> 39:34.622
A week ago
he refused to take $20 for a public fish.

39:34.706 --> 39:38.251
That's very commendable.
I think that... How is that?

39:38.376 --> 39:40.170
It doesn't really matter.

39:40.253 --> 39:43.047
I happen to have
a very high opinion of honesty.

39:43.715 --> 39:45.925
Well, yes, sir, of course.

39:46.009 --> 39:47.510
But is it security?

39:49.512 --> 39:53.266
It just might be that this is
the only real security there is.

39:54.225 --> 39:57.687
Well, sir, I became
a vice president of this bank

39:57.770 --> 40:01.065
because I made it a habit
never to contradict the boss.

40:04.235 --> 40:07.030
This bank is about to lend you $2,000.

40:08.364 --> 40:12.035
We're very grateful, sir,
but I don't want to try to fool anybody.

40:12.118 --> 40:14.829
Now that car of Pop's is in a terrible mess.

40:14.913 --> 40:16.206
It doesn't matter, Toby.

40:16.289 --> 40:18.958
What we're making is known
as a character loan.

40:19.250 --> 40:23.129
We do it now and then, but not
often enough for the good of our souls.

40:25.048 --> 40:26.424
Don't you agree, George?

40:26.508 --> 40:28.968
Oh, yeah. Oh, yes. Yes, sir.

40:30.803 --> 40:33.431
Well, nice having done
business with you, Toby.

40:33.556 --> 40:34.599
Thank you, Mr. Endicott.

40:34.724 --> 40:36.267
- And you, Holly.
- Thank you, sir.

40:42.941 --> 40:44.400
- Oh, Mr. King.
- Yes?

40:44.484 --> 40:46.110
Miss Claypoole's office just called.

40:46.194 --> 40:47.862
She has your memo
and she can see you now.

40:47.946 --> 40:49.822
Good. Call her back
and tell her <i>I'l</i> l be right there.

40:49.948 --> 40:50.990
Yes, sir.

40:51.282 --> 40:53.117
(CHATTERING QUIETLY)

40:59.249 --> 41:01.876
Well, I gather you don't think
highly of these Kwimper people.

41:01.960 --> 41:04.128
You gather good.

41:05.296 --> 41:07.757
They sound half hillbilly, half hobo to me.

41:07.840 --> 41:11.844
With a tincture of Bowery burn
and possibly wino.

41:13.179 --> 41:15.682
Well, Arthur,
if this memo of yours is correct,

41:15.765 --> 41:16.891
this is a case for the police,

41:16.975 --> 41:18.476
not for Social Welfare.

41:18.601 --> 41:21.187
Does the memo imply
they've broken the law?

41:21.312 --> 41:23.940
I don't recall making any such statement.

41:24.148 --> 41:28.528
Well, it says, "A social contagion
that aims its poison of indifference

41:29.612 --> 41:32.490
"and sloth at the soul
of our social structure."

41:33.616 --> 41:35.410
Well, is that funny?

41:36.077 --> 41:37.120
No.

41:37.203 --> 41:39.872
Sorry, Arthur,
you do get a bit stuffy when you get angry.

41:39.998 --> 41:43.042
Yes, Alisha, when a few parasitic individuals

41:43.167 --> 41:44.544
set themselves above the interests

41:44.669 --> 41:48.339
of six million taxpayers, I get angry,
and stuffy, and determined!

41:51.009 --> 41:53.678
Well, if these people
are what you represent,

41:53.803 --> 41:57.015
the State Welfare can
make them want to be someplace else.

41:57.140 --> 42:00.435
But I'm afraid I can't take your word for it,
I'll have to interview them.

42:00.518 --> 42:04.188
Alisha, how dare you imply
I'd misrepresent this situation?

42:05.023 --> 42:07.108
Arthur, keep your shirt on.

42:07.191 --> 42:09.402
You've already admitted you were angry.

42:09.986 --> 42:14.032
Now what Welfare Officer would take the
recommendations of an angry man, hmm?

42:14.657 --> 42:17.452
And remember,
I didn't take this job for livelihood.

42:17.535 --> 42:18.745
I enjoy my work.

42:19.537 --> 42:22.832
I must say, interviewing the Kwimpers
does look like a lot of fun.

42:32.050 --> 42:33.718
Good morning, Holly.

42:34.010 --> 42:35.136
Good morning, folks.

42:35.219 --> 42:36.721
Did you get my yarn I needed?

42:36.804 --> 42:39.390
Yeah, <i>I'l</i> l bring it over in a few minutes.

42:39.515 --> 42:41.517
Pop, Toby, it's last Sunday's.

42:41.601 --> 42:43.645
The man at the fishing tackle
place saved it for me.

42:43.728 --> 42:45.063
Now, listen,

42:45.188 --> 42:47.649
"New Bay Development
Open to Homesteading.

42:47.732 --> 42:50.068
"New Enterprise to Cater for Fishing Parties.

42:50.526 --> 42:53.404
"The exact status at this newly created
bay development

42:53.488 --> 42:54.864
"is a bit of a puzzle.

42:54.947 --> 42:58.368
"It cannot be restricted
by municipal or county ordinances

42:58.451 --> 43:00.370
"as it lies outside theirjurisdiction."

43:00.453 --> 43:03.247
Now, hold on, Holly, you're turning
my head with talking so fast...

43:03.373 --> 43:04.499
But, Toby...

43:04.582 --> 43:08.044
Son, that means that the city
or the county ain't got no say over us.

43:08.127 --> 43:10.922
Even their police can't come in here
and tell us what to do.

43:11.047 --> 43:12.715
That's why we got a lot of neighbors.

43:12.799 --> 43:15.176
See, folks can take so much government,

43:15.259 --> 43:18.179
then they gotta bust out
and go where there ain't none.

43:18.262 --> 43:19.681
Understand, son?

43:19.764 --> 43:21.307
(STUTTERING) I think so, Pop, I...

43:21.432 --> 43:22.934
(HORN HONKING)

43:32.944 --> 43:36.072
It's kind of funny,
all them fellows living in one trailer, ain't it?

43:36.155 --> 43:38.116
Ain't no business of ours.

43:41.786 --> 43:42.829
(WATER GURGLING)

43:49.627 --> 43:51.295
Too much pressure.

43:52.463 --> 43:54.006
- Too much pressure.
- Yep.

43:55.633 --> 43:57.427
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

44:07.103 --> 44:09.814
You know,
maybe we should pay them a call, huh?

44:10.273 --> 44:12.817
Sounds to me like they got enough callers.

44:12.942 --> 44:16.529
Well, I just don't feel right
acting standoffish to neighbors.

44:17.947 --> 44:19.991
Suit yourself, Holly.

44:20.450 --> 44:23.494
Toby, come on with me.
I'll take them some coffee.

44:23.619 --> 44:25.788
Don't wanna go empty-handed.

44:26.330 --> 44:27.790
It's your move, Pop.

44:27.874 --> 44:29.333
I know it, son.

44:32.503 --> 44:34.380
Here, it's nice and fresh.

44:39.218 --> 44:40.845
(DOOR CLOSING)

44:54.066 --> 44:55.902
MAN: All right, punk,
where do you think you're going?

44:56.027 --> 44:57.570
- MAN 1: Hold it right there.
- Give me that.

44:57.695 --> 44:58.905
TOBY: Watch it, you'll make me spill it.

44:58.988 --> 45:00.490
MAN 1: What do you got there?

45:00.573 --> 45:03.451
Hey, look at the popsie.
She's got a knife on her.

45:03.534 --> 45:04.577
Give me that.

45:04.702 --> 45:06.037
(GROANING)

45:06.162 --> 45:07.538
(SCREAMING)

45:08.873 --> 45:09.874
What is this?

45:09.957 --> 45:11.709
This punk threw acid on my hand.

45:11.793 --> 45:14.420
You'd better watch it, Carmine, that dame,
she slashed me with a knife.

45:14.504 --> 45:16.297
I never did anything of the kind.

45:16.380 --> 45:17.632
All right, hold it you two.
Put a flash on them.

45:17.715 --> 45:19.509
Look, we're just trying to be neighborly.

45:19.592 --> 45:23.095
I'm sorry you fellows got hurt,
but you done it to yourselves.

45:23.221 --> 45:25.890
A pot of coffee and a can opener.

45:26.641 --> 45:28.601
A couple of great muscle men you are.

45:28.684 --> 45:30.186
Holly here made you some coffee.

45:30.269 --> 45:31.312
Would you like to try some?

45:31.395 --> 45:34.190
Sure thing.
You two must be from next door.

45:34.273 --> 45:35.483
Yeah, glad to meet you.

45:35.566 --> 45:36.609
Pleased to meet you.

45:36.692 --> 45:39.904
Would you like to come inside,
meet my partner, Nick?

45:41.239 --> 45:44.242
If you put some butter on it,
it'll take the sting out of it.

45:44.367 --> 45:45.910
- Come on in.
- Thanks.

45:47.703 --> 45:48.871
What's that?

45:48.955 --> 45:49.997
What's what?

45:50.456 --> 45:52.667
Well, Holly ain't never been nowhere.

45:52.750 --> 45:54.585
That's a pool table, honey.

45:54.710 --> 45:57.004
First one I ever seen
without pockets, though.

45:57.088 --> 46:01.259
Yeah, well, you just cover the bet
and make yourself some easy money, Sam.

46:01.384 --> 46:02.593
(PEOPLE CHATTERING)

46:05.805 --> 46:08.057
What did you do, send out for something?

46:08.140 --> 46:10.351
No, Nick, these people are from next door.

46:10.434 --> 46:12.228
They brought us some coffee.

46:12.478 --> 46:13.855
Coffee? What for?

46:13.938 --> 46:15.106
You drink it.

46:17.567 --> 46:18.943
Is he kidding?

46:19.068 --> 46:21.153
I don't think so. He's like that.

46:21.279 --> 46:23.781
Well, Toby and I just
like to be neighborly, that's all.

46:23.906 --> 46:25.658
Sure, do you want me to pour you a cup?

46:25.783 --> 46:29.036
No, no, no, bud, look,
we're not neighbors.

46:29.120 --> 46:30.580
This is a floating game, see?

46:30.788 --> 46:32.832
We just stick around
in one place until it gets too hot.

46:32.915 --> 46:34.500
Then we move along. Get it?

46:34.584 --> 46:37.211
Oh, sure. Well, they tell me
it don't get hot around here

46:37.295 --> 46:39.463
till about the middle of July.

46:42.008 --> 46:44.176
He is like that, ain't he?

46:44.427 --> 46:48.222
No, you see, it gets hot
for us anyplace we go after a couple of days.

46:48.306 --> 46:51.767
Well, if it gets hot anyplace,
what did you come here for?

46:51.851 --> 46:53.644
Well, it was on the way.

46:53.853 --> 46:56.898
Oh, then you're not just running away
from the government.

46:56.981 --> 46:58.274
What was that?

46:58.357 --> 47:00.234
Well, Toby thinks maybe you

47:00.318 --> 47:03.112
saw that piece in the paper
about there being no government.

47:03.195 --> 47:04.739
No, what kind of government?

47:04.822 --> 47:07.491
Well, it said that
the State built this here land

47:07.617 --> 47:11.203
and the county ain't
got no say-so over it, the city neither.

47:12.121 --> 47:14.498
Hey, could this be on the level?

47:14.624 --> 47:17.376
You know, it sounds screwy enough,
it could be kosher.

47:17.501 --> 47:19.587
That's what it sounds like to me.

47:19.670 --> 47:22.882
Oh, baby, this kind of a chance
comes along once in a lifetime.

47:23.007 --> 47:26.260
Carmine, you know this could turn out
to be an East Coast Las Vegas.

47:26.344 --> 47:28.638
Oh, you mean
because there's no police here?

47:28.721 --> 47:30.097
Now you're digging it, little lady.

47:30.181 --> 47:32.224
Yes, but what about after we file?

47:32.350 --> 47:34.060
- File what?
- Our claim.

47:34.185 --> 47:37.063
Once we've lived here for six months,
we can claim the land.

47:37.188 --> 47:39.815
Pop says that it'll be part of the county then.

47:39.899 --> 47:43.069
Well, this land claiming idea
don't sound too good.

47:43.194 --> 47:45.363
Now, I bet it would
if Pop explained it to you.

47:45.488 --> 47:48.532
Yeah, well, where is he?
In that woodpile next door?

47:48.741 --> 47:51.410
Well, he wasn't in the woodpile
when we left. He was...

47:51.535 --> 47:54.580
Well, let's visit him anyway.
After you, please.

47:54.705 --> 47:56.082
Thank you, sir.

47:56.207 --> 47:57.583
(CHUCKUNG)

47:59.085 --> 48:00.962
Oh, baby, is this a sweet deal?

48:01.045 --> 48:03.714
Carmine, nobody's gonna mess it up.

48:04.048 --> 48:05.967
You're not planning any rough stuff?

48:06.050 --> 48:08.010
We do it nice if we can.

48:11.013 --> 48:14.183
Now, your kid here tells me
you're gonna put in a claim for this land?

48:14.266 --> 48:15.977
That's about the size of it.

48:16.060 --> 48:19.313
Well, that would be a big mistake.
Bring the cops here.

48:19.397 --> 48:22.441
Right nice of you to warn us
but I know all about it.

48:23.234 --> 48:25.903
